issues.title: SNOW-770796: Hide credentials from exception when connection url fails to parse
issues.body:
# Overview

SNOW-770796

1. If the driver fails to parse a provided connection url, it returns 'null' to the driver manager for the getConnection() function. The driver manager throws an exception which exposes credentials if they are specified directly in the connection url. 

2. If the connection url contains an illegal character a URLSyntaxException will be thrown which will also expose the credentials from the url.

example:
```
2023-03-29 21:12:35.200 n.s.c.jdbc.SnowflakeConnectString WARNING parse:157 - Exception thrown while parsing Snowflake connect string
Exception in thread "main" java.sql.SQLException: No suitable driver found for jdbc:snowflake://testaccount.snowflakecomputing.com/?warehouse=test_wh&db=test_db&private_key_file=C:\temp\rsa_key.p8&user=user123&private_key_file_pwd=password123
	at java.sql.DriverManager.getConnection(DriverManager.java:689)
	at java.sql.DriverManager.getConnection(DriverManager.java:270)
	at TestConnection.testUrl(TestConnection.java:753)
	at TestConnection.main(TestConnection.java:52)
```

## External contributors - please answer these questions before submitting a pull request. Thanks!

Please answer these questions before submitting your pull requests. Thanks!

1. What GitHub issue is this PR addressing? Make sure that there is an accompanying issue to your PR.

   Fixes [#297 ](https://github.com/snowflakedb/snowflake-sdks-drivers-issues-teamwork/issues/297)


4. Fill out the following pre-review checklist:

5. Please describe how your code solves the related issue.

 1.  If the driver fails to parse the connection url, throw an exception rather than returning a 'null' connection to the DriverManager.
 
 2. Catch the URISyntaxException and log a more discrete message.

issues.title: [SNOW-804206]Fix ConfigFile parser issues in Windows
issues.body:
# Overview
SNOW-804206 
Context: As part of easy logging configuration, we have introduced a new config file where users can configure log level and log path. This PR fixes build issues introduced by earlier PR: https://github.com/snowflakedb/snowflake-jdbc/pull/1384 in windows os. 

```
Exception in thread "main" java.nio.file.InvalidPathException: Illegal char <:> at index 2: /C:/git/snowflake-jdbc/target/classes/sf_config.json
	at java.base/sun.nio.fs.WindowsPathParser.normalize(WindowsPathParser.java:182)
	at java.base/sun.nio.fs.WindowsPathParser.parse(WindowsPathParser.java:153)

	at java.base/java.nio.file.Paths.get(Paths.java:69)
	at TestConnection.testQuery(TestConnection.java:218)
	at TestConnection.main(TestConnection.java:71)
```

- Updated the `getConfigFilePathFromJDBCJarLocation` method to handle file location in windows os.

issues.title: SNOW-852665: Allow ~ in PUT/GET file path
issues.body:
# Overview

SNOW-852665

PUT commands will fail if the source file path contains ~ even though this is accepted in folder names. This is because during parsing of the command, the driver filters out any ~ with the user home directory.

```
for (String path : filePathList) {
      // replace ~ with user home
      path = path.replace("~", systemGetProperty("user.home"));
```

So file path in the command `"PUT 'file:///C:/snowflake~/test.txt' '@~' AUTO_COMPRESS=FALSE"` would be parsed to "`/C:/snowflakeC:\Users\user/test.txt`"

GET commands will also fail if trying to download to a directory with ~ in the path name. This is because the driver checks if ~ is at the start of the command, then replaces with the user home directory. Afterwards it checks to see if the command still contains an ~ and will throw a PATH_NOT_DIRECTORY error.

```
      if (localLocation.startsWith("~")) {
        // replace ~ with user home
        localLocation = systemGetProperty("user.home") + localLocation.substring(1);
      }

      // it should not contain any ~ after the above replacement
      if (localLocation.contains("~")) {
        throw new SnowflakeSQLLoggedException(
            session,
            ErrorCode.PATH_NOT_DIRECTORY.getMessageCode(),
            SqlState.IO_ERROR,
            localLocation);
      }
```

## External contributors - please answer these questions before submitting a pull request. Thanks!

Please answer these questions before submitting your pull requests. Thanks!

1. What GitHub issue is this PR addressing? Make sure that there is an accompanying issue to your PR.

   Fixes #1458 
   https://github.com/snowflakedb/snowflake-sdks-drivers-issues-teamwork/issues/508

2. Fill out the following pre-review checklist:

   - [ ] I am adding a new automated test(s) to verify correctness of my new code
   - [ ] I am adding new logging messages
   - [ ] I am modifying authorization mechanisms
   - [ ] I am adding new credentials
   - [ ] I am modifying OCSP code
   - [ ] I am adding a new dependency

3. Please describe how your code solves the related issue.

   Ensure that ~ is only replaced for PUT/GET if it's at the start of the command. Otherwise, allow ~ in folder directories.

## Pre-review checklist
- [ ] This change has passed precommit
- [ ] I have reviewed code coverage report for my PR in  ([Sonarqube](https://sonarqube.int.snowflakecomputing.com/project/branches?id=snowflake-jdbc))
